Finally, we find that PL emission from these metal NCs are very stable under picosecond laser excitation at 355 nm, and no degradation of their PL intensity was observed even with an excitation of 8 mJ per pulse with a spot size of 1–2 mm. Moreover, we explored the PL intensity vs pump laser excitation at 355 nm and results are shown in Figs 5 and 6. Integrated PL intensity in Figs 5 and 6 was obtained as the area under the experimental PL curve for each pump fluence excitation. As it can be seen from Figs 5 and 6, the initial part of the PL intensity vs pump power is linear and tends to be saturated as the irradiance increases. At higher power pump excitation, the PL intensity takes an upward turn and increases superlinearly. The increase of PL scales quadratically with the pump fluence, IPL~Pexc2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
